const a = [
  {"id":1380,"text":"During translation, the initiation codon of mRNA attaches to the ribosome at which site?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sanvictores T, Farci F. Biochemistry, primary protein structure. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 9, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564343/","responses":[{"text":"E site of 30S subunit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A site of 30S subunit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"P site of 30S subunit","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A site of 50S subunit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"E site of 50S subunit","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11520,"text":"Which enzyme is responsible for releasing DNA supercoils?","explanation":"The enzyme responsible for releasing DNA supercoils is **topoisomerase**. Topoisomerases are essential enzymes that manage the topological states of DNA. They function by transiently cutting one or both strands of the DNA helix, allowing for the relaxation of supercoils that form during processes like DNA replication and transcription, and then resealing the breaks. This activity is crucial for the proper functioning of DNA replication and transcription, as supercoiled DNA can hinder the progress of DNA and RNA polymerases. \r\n\r\nDNA ligase is involved in joining DNA strands together, particularly during DNA replication and repair. RNA polymerase is responsible for synthesizing RNA from a DNA template. Helicase unwinds the double-stranded DNA helix into single strands, facilitating replication or transcription. Single-strand DNA is not an enzyme but a product of DNA unwinding.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 417.","responses":[{"text":"Helicase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single strand DNA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"RNA polymerase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Topoisomerase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"DNA ligase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16953,"text":"Which of the following cells is not a component of connective tissue?","explanation":"**Goblet cells** are specialized epithelial cells primarily found in the mucous membranes lining various organs, such as the respiratory and digestive tracts. These cells play a crucial role in the production and secretion of mucus, a thick and slimy substance that helps lubricate and protect the epithelial surfaces. While they are involved in the maintenance of mucosal integrity, they are distinct from the cells commonly associated with connective tissue.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 86.","responses":[{"text":"Chondrocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histiocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Goblet cell","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adipocyte","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19345,"text":"A radiologist noticed a fracture of a bone that connects the axial skeleton with the appendicular skeleton on an X-ray. What is the regional classification of the fractured bone?","explanation":"The radiologist's observation of a fracture connecting the axial skeleton with the appendicular skeleton on an X-ray indicates that the fractured bone falls under the **appendicular** regional classification.\r\n\r\nIn anatomical terms, the human skeleton is divided into two main regions: the **axial skeleton** and the **appendicular skeleton**. The axial skeleton comprises the bones along the central axis of the body, which includes the skull, vertebral column, and ribcage. On the other hand, the appendicular skeleton consists of the bones that form the limbs and the girdles that attach the limbs to the axial skeleton. These include the bones of the arms, legs, shoulders (scapulae), and hips (pelvic girdle).\r\n\r\nThe fractured bone that connects these two regions is typically one of the bones in the shoulder or pelvic girdles. These girdles serve as the junctions between the axial and appendicular skeletons, allowing for the attachment and movement of the limbs. Therefore, when a fracture occurs at this juncture, it is classified as an **appendicular** bone fracture.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 143.","responses":[{"text":"Membranous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cancellous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Compact","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appendicular","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cartilaginous","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19346,"text":"A 65-year-old female came to the emergency with a hip bone fracture due to slipping on a wet floor. An X-ray revealed she has osteoporosis, which has weakened her bones to a point where they can easily break. Which type of bone is fractured?","explanation":"**Hip bone** is an example of irregular bones. **Irregular bones** are defined by their complex shapes and are not classified as long, short, or flat. Their interior is made up of cancellous bone surrounded by a shell of compact bone. Other examples include bones of the skull and vertebrae.\r\n\r\n----\r\n\r\n\r\nSesamoid bones are small bones that are embedded within tendons, providing protection and improving mechanical efficiency. They are usually found near joints, such as the patella (kneecap).\r\n\r\nFlat bones are thin, flat bones that provide protection to underlying organs and contribute to hematopoiesis (blood cell production) in some cases. Examples of flat bones include the skull bones, sternum, and ribs.\r\n\r\n Long bones are characterized by their elongated shape and consist of a shaft (diaphysis) and expanded ends (epiphyses). Examples of long bones include the femur, tibia, and humerus.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 554.","responses":[{"text":"Short","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irregular","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sesamoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Long","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19347,"text":"A 21-year-old medical student decides to take a nap after having his lunch. Which of the following nervous systems is activated?","explanation":"When the 21-year-old medical student decides to take a nap after lunch, his **parasympathetic nervous system** is primarily activated. The autonomic nervous system, which consists of both the sympathetic and parasympathetic divisions, controls involuntary bodily functions, including those related to rest and digestion.\r\n\r\nThe parasympathetic nervous system is often referred to as the \"rest and digest\" system because it promotes activities associated with a state of relaxation and recovery. When activated, it works to conserve energy and restore the body's resources. This is in contrast to the **sympathetic nervous system**, which is responsible for the \"fight or flight\" response and prepares the body for action and stress.\r\n\r\nDuring the post-lunch period, especially when an individual is in a relaxed environment and intends to rest, the parasympathetic nervous system predominates. It slows down the heart rate, reduces blood pressure, and promotes digestion and nutrient absorption, creating an optimal state for rest and recovery.","reference":"LeBouef T, Yaker Z, Whited L. Physiology, autonomic nervous system. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed September 12, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538516/","responses":[{"text":"Peripheral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parasympathetic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sympathetic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autonomic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19348,"text":"Within the cell, DNA is in the nucleus. Which other structure within the cell organelles listed below also contains DNA?","explanation":"Among the cell organelles listed, **mitochondria** are the structures that, in addition to the nucleus, also contain DNA. This DNA within the mitochondria is often referred to as **mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA)**.\r\n\r\nMitochondria are often called the \"powerhouses\" of the cell because they play a crucial role in generating energy in the form of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) through a process called oxidative phosphorylation. Interestingly, mitochondria are unique among organelles because they contain their own DNA, which is separate from the cell's nuclear DNA.\r\n\r\nThis mitochondrial DNA is essential for the proper functioning of mitochondria. It encodes some of the proteins and RNA necessary for the mitochondria's energy-producing processes. Unlike nuclear DNA, which is inherited from both parents, mitochondrial DNA is usually inherited exclusively from the mother.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 39.","responses":[{"text":"Mitochondria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroxisome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Smooth endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Golgi apparatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rough endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19349,"text":"A 32-year-old female suffering from lifelong atopic eczema comes to her dermatologist with a rash on her hand, which appeared after direct contact with dish soap. She has a history of rash from wearing certain clothing and jewelry. Which layer of skin is found only in thick skin?","explanation":"The skin consists of several layers, with the outermost layer being the **epidermis**, which is responsible for protecting the body from the external environment. In **thick skin**, which is typically found in areas subject to more wear and tear, such as the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet, there is an additional layer known as the **stratum lucidum**.\r\n\r\nThe **stratum lucidum** is a clear, translucent layer situated between the stratum corneum and the stratum granulosum. It contains flattened, densely packed keratinocytes (skin cells) that lack nuclei and other organelles. This layer plays a role in the thick skin's unique properties, providing additional protection against friction and mechanical stress.\r\n\r\nIn individuals with a history of atopic eczema, the skin's barrier function may be compromised, making them more susceptible to skin reactions when exposed to certain irritants like dish soap, clothing, or jewelry. The rash on the hand after contact with dish soap could be an example of contact dermatitis, where irritants trigger an inflammatory response in the skin.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 374.","responses":[{"text":"Stratum granulosum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratum lucidum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratum spinosum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratum corneum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratum germinativum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19350,"text":"A patient comes to an emergency with a patellar fracture due to an automobile accident. An X-ray confirmed several small fragments of the patella, and the knee is in a semi-flexed position. Which type of bone is fractured?","explanation":"The type of bone fractured in the case of the patellar fracture resulting from an automobile accident is a **sesamoid bone**. \r\n\r\nSesamoid bones are a unique category of bones that develop within tendons or in regions where tendons pass over joints. The patella, commonly known as the kneecap, is the largest sesamoid bone in the human body. It is embedded within the tendon of the quadriceps femoris muscle and is located over the anterior surface of the knee joint.\r\n\r\nThe patella serves an essential function in the biomechanics of the knee joint. It acts as a fulcrum, increasing the leverage of the quadriceps muscle over the knee joint, thus enhancing the extension of the leg. It also provides protection to the knee joint by preventing excessive wear and tear on the joint surface during movements like walking, running, and jumping.\r\n\r\nIn cases of trauma, such as the automobile accident described, the patella can fracture into several small fragments due to the forces applied to the knee joint. This can result in a semi-flexed position of the knee, along with pain and swelling, requiring medical evaluation and intervention. Fractures of the patella are typically managed with immobilization, surgical intervention, or a combination of both, depending on the severity and displacement of the fracture fragments.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 678.","responses":[{"text":"Long","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irregular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sesamoid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19365,"text":"A 20-day-old neonate was diagnosed with chronic diarrhea. The consultant explained to the resident that this was due to the defect in the surface modification of the epithelial lining of the small intestine leading to severe diarrhea and malnutrition. Which of the following is defective in the above case?","explanation":"**Microvilli** are tiny, finger-like projections on the surface of the small intestinal epithelial cells, particularly on the cells known as enterocytes. These structures greatly increase the surface area of the small intestine, which is essential for efficient absorption of nutrients and water from digested food.\r\n\r\nMicrovilli contain various enzymes and transport proteins that aid in the digestion and absorption of nutrients, including carbohydrates, proteins, and lipids. In cases where there is a defect in the microvilli, such as in conditions like congenital microvillus inclusion disease (CMVID), the absorptive capacity of the small intestine is severely compromised. This leads to malabsorption of nutrients, chronic diarrhea, and malnutrition, as seen in the neonate.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 77.","responses":[{"text":"Sterocilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microvilli","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Villi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flagella","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19366,"text":"During a histology lecture, the professor discussed about function of epithelium that allows the rapid exchange of gases, active transport by pinocytosis and facilitates movement of viscera and secretions of biologically active substances. Which of the following epithelium types is being described above?","explanation":"The type of epithelium described here is **simple squamous epithelium**. Simple squamous epithelium is a single layer of flattened cells that forms a delicate, thin tissue. It serves several crucial functions in the body.\r\n\r\nSimple squamous epithelium is found in structures where rapid gas exchange occurs, such as in the alveoli of the lungs. Its thin nature allows for efficient diffusion of oxygen and carbon dioxide between blood and air. Additionally, despite its thinness, simple squamous epithelium remains selectively permeable, allowing it to actively transport substances across its surface. This includes processes like pinocytosis, where cells engulf fluids and solutes from their surroundings.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, this type of epithelium lines structures involved in the movement of viscera (organs) and the secretion of biologically active substances. For example, it lines the inner surface of blood vessels (endothelium) and serous membranes (mesothelium), contributing to the lubrication of internal organs.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 82.","responses":[{"text":"Simple squamous","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transitional","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified columnar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple cuboidal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudostratified","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19367,"text":"Urine is confined to the urinary bladder due to the cell junctions that connect the cell to the urinary bladder. These junctions form a barrier that prevents the exchange of ions and solutes between blood and urine. What is the likely identity of these junctions?","explanation":"**Tight junctions** are the critical structures responsible for confining urine within the urinary bladder and creating a barrier that prevents the exchange of ions and solutes between the blood and urine. \r\n\r\nThese specialized junctions form a belt-like structure near the apical surface of the epithelial cells lining the urinary bladder. They consist of transmembrane proteins that seal adjacent cells together, creating an impermeable barrier. One of the key functions of tight junctions is to limit the paracellular transport of substances, ensuring that urine remains separate from the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nTight junctions are particularly vital in the urinary system, as they help regulate the movement of water, ions, and waste products. By maintaining a tight barrier between the urinary space and the bloodstream, they contribute to the concentration and composition of urine.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 408.","responses":[{"text":"Tight junction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Desmosome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gap junction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zonula adherens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemidesmosome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19404,"text":"A researcher is investigating the protein utilized by hemidesmosomes to form an attachment to the extracellular matrix. Which of the following proteins is the researcher investigating?","explanation":"**Integrins** are crucial proteins that facilitate the attachment of hemidesmosomes to the extracellular matrix (ECM). These transmembrane proteins play a pivotal role in cell adhesion, particularly in connecting cells to the ECM.\r\n\r\nIntegrins extend from the cell membrane, where they interact with specific ECM proteins like laminin and collagen. This interaction forms a robust anchoring point, securing the cell to the ECM. On the cytoplasmic side of the cell membrane, integrins connect with intracellular proteins, including desmoplakin and plectin. These intracellular proteins, in turn, link to intermediate filaments such as keratin, creating a stable bridge from the cell membrane to the cytoskeleton.\r\n\r\nHemidesmosomes, facilitated by integrins, are vital for maintaining the structural integrity of epithelial tissues. They ensure that cells remain firmly attached to the underlying basement membrane, providing stability and resistance to mechanical stress.","reference":"Walko G, Castañón MJ, Wiche G. Molecular architecture and function of the hemidesmosome. Cell and Tissue Research. Published 2015. Accessed September 14, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4452579/","responses":[{"text":"Desmoplakin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Desmoglein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Integrins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cadherins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Desmocollin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19405,"text":"A histopathologist is observing a slide of muscular tissue under a microscope showing striations and peripherally located multiple nuclei. \r\nWhich of the following triads is a feature of this tissue?","explanation":"The histopathologist is examining a slide of muscular tissue characterized by striations and the presence of peripherally located multiple nuclei. This tissue exhibits a unique feature known as the **triad**, which consists of **1 T-tubule and 2 sarcoplasmic reticulum** structures.\r\n\r\n**T-Tubule (transverse tubule):** These are invaginations of the cell membrane (sarcolemma) that penetrate deep into the muscle fiber. T-tubules play a crucial role in transmitting action potentials (nerve signals) from the cell surface to the interior of the muscle fiber, ensuring synchronous muscle contraction.\r\n\r\n**Sarcoplasmic reticulum:** The sarcoplasmic reticulum is a specialized type of endoplasmic reticulum found in muscle cells. It plays a vital role in regulating intracellular calcium levels. The sarcoplasmic reticulum stores and releases calcium ions during muscle contraction and relaxation, which is essential for muscle function.\r\n\r\nThe triad is a key structural arrangement in muscle cells, facilitating the coordinated contraction of muscle fibers. The T-tubule and adjacent sarcoplasmic reticulum components work together to ensure that the muscle receives the appropriate signals and calcium ions for effective contraction and relaxation, enabling precise control over muscle movement.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 198.","responses":[{"text":"2 T-tubules and 1 sarcoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 T-tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3 sarcoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1 T-tubule and 2 sarcoplasmic reticulum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"3 T-tubules","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19407,"text":"Under microscope examination, a single layer of tall cells is found resting on the basement membrane. The height of the cell is greater as compared to its thickness with basally placed nuclei. Which of the following tissues is being observed?","explanation":"The tissue being observed under the microscope, characterized by a single layer of tall cells resting on the basement membrane, with basally placed nuclei, is **found in the GIT (gastrointestinal tract) from the stomach to the rectum**. This tissue is specifically known as **simple columnar epithelium**.\r\n\r\nSimple columnar epithelium is well-suited for various functions along the gastrointestinal tract. The tall and slender shape of the cells allows for efficient absorption and secretion. The basally placed nuclei are a characteristic feature of this tissue, providing stability to the cells and allowing for a uniform height.\r\n\r\nIn the stomach, this epithelium helps protect against the acidic environment and secretes mucus to lubricate the surface. In the small intestine, it plays a crucial role in absorption due to the presence of microvilli on the apical surface of the cells, increasing the surface area for nutrient absorption. In the large intestine, it is involved in absorption and secretion of fluids and electrolytes.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 82.","responses":[{"text":"Alveoli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid follicle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrointestinal tract (from stomach to rectum)","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19477,"text":"Which of the following drugs results in phocomelia in case of its exposure during development?","explanation":"**Thalidomide** exposure during development is known to result in a condition called **phocomelia**. Phocomelia is a severe limb deformity where the limbs are extremely shortened and flipper-like, resembling the limbs of seals (phoco means seal in Greek). This condition occurs when thalidomide is taken during the critical period of limb development in the embryo, usually during the first trimester of pregnancy.\r\n\r\nThalidomide was once marketed as a sedative and anti-nausea medication for pregnant women in the late 1950s and early 1960s. Tragically, it was later discovered that thalidomide caused severe birth defects, particularly affecting the development of the limbs. This led to a significant medical scandal and prompted strict regulations on drug safety and testing.\r\n\r\nThe mechanism of thalidomide-induced phocomelia is not completely understood, but it is believed to interfere with blood vessel development and the formation of limb buds during embryogenesis. Due to its teratogenic effects, thalidomide is no longer used during pregnancy and serves as a cautionary example of the importance of rigorous drug testing and safety measures during pregnancy.","reference":"Davis DD, Kane SM. Phocomelia. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed September 17, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559212/","responses":[{"text":"Alcohol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aminoglycoside","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thalidomide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulphonamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetracycline","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19479,"text":"During development, which of the following has totipotent cells?","explanation":"During development, the totipotent cells are found in the **zygote**. The zygote is the initial cell formed when the sperm fertilizes the egg. It contains the complete set of genetic information from both parents and has the remarkable ability to give rise to all the cell types needed to form a complete organism.\r\n\r\nTotipotent cells have the highest developmental potential among all cell types. They can differentiate into any cell type in the body, including cells of the embryonic and extraembryonic tissues. This unique characteristic is essential for the early stages of embryonic development when the zygote divides and gives rise to the morula and later the blastocyst.\r\n\r\nAs development progresses, these totipotent cells become more specialized through a process called differentiation, eventually forming the various tissues and organs of the developing embryo. Totipotent cells are crucial for the formation of the complete organism and play a pivotal role in the early stages of embryogenesis.","reference":"Hu K. On mammalian totipotency: what is the molecular underpinning for the totipotency of zygote? Stem Cells and Development. Published July 15, 2019. Accessed September 17, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6648208/","responses":[{"text":"Outer cell mass","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zygote","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Embryoblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trophoblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytotrophoblast","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19480,"text":"A zygote undergoes which of the following mechanisms after fertilization?","explanation":"After fertilization, the zygote embarks on a complex series of developmental events to give rise to the multicellular organism it will become. This process is known as **cleavage formation**. \r\n\r\nCleavage involves a rapid sequence of cell divisions without an increase in the overall size of the embryo. These divisions produce progressively smaller cells called blastomeres. Cleavage serves two essential purposes: first, it partitions the cytoplasmic components of the zygote into smaller cells, and second, it increases the total cell number.\r\n\r\nCleavage sets the stage for subsequent processes in embryonic development, such as gastrulation, neurulation, and blastocyst formation. Gastrulation involves the formation of the three primary germ layers (ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm) and is a pivotal step in tissue differentiation. Neurulation leads to the development of the nervous system. Blastocyst formation occurs as the embryo undergoes compaction and cavity formation.\r\n\r\nFinally, implantation follows cleavage and is the process by which the developing embryo attaches to and embeds within the uterine lining, marking the beginning of pregnancy.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 42.","responses":[{"text":"Blastocyst formation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cleavage formation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Implantation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19481,"text":"Which of the following is not classified as a structural chromosomal abnormality?","explanation":"Structural chromosomal abnormalities encompass various alterations in the structure of chromosomes. These changes can lead to genetic disorders or developmental abnormalities.\r\n\r\nTrisomy refers to the presence of an extra copy of an entire chromosome, resulting in three copies instead of the usual two. It is a numerical chromosomal abnormality, not a structural one. Trisomies, such as Trisomy 21 (Down syndrome), involve an extra whole chromosome, rather than changes in the structure or arrangement of chromosome segments.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, structural chromosomal abnormalities include insertion, deletion, translocation, and inversion. These abnormalities involve alterations in the arrangement or structure of specific chromosome segments, which can have significant clinical implications and may lead to genetic disorders.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 17-18.","responses":[{"text":"Inversion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insertion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deletion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Translocation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trisomy","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19534,"text":"A first-year medical student was observing the metaphase of meiosis. How can he differentiate it from the metaphase of mitosis?","explanation":"One key feature that distinguishes meiotic metaphase from mitotic metaphase is **homologous pairing**. During meiotic metaphase, homologous chromosomes (one from each parent) align at the cell's equatorial plane. This alignment allows for the subsequent separation of homologous chromosomes during meiosis I, a crucial step that leads to genetic diversity in offspring. In contrast, during mitotic metaphase, there is no homologous pairing, as the goal is to produce two genetically identical daughter cells.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, during meiotic metaphase, there is often a visible phenomenon known as the **crossing over** between homologous chromosomes. This exchange of genetic material further contributes to genetic diversity. Such events do not occur during mitotic metaphase.\r\n\r\nAnother distinction lies in the **number of cell divisions**. Meiosis involves two successive divisions, resulting in four non-identical haploid daughter cells, whereas mitosis involves one division, yielding two identical diploid daughter cells.\r\n\r\nLastly, in mitotic metaphase, the cell proceeds to divide into two daughter cells by **cytokinesis**, while in meiotic metaphase, this division of the cytoplasm does not occur until after meiosis II.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 16.","responses":[{"text":"Reformation of nuclear membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disappearance of nuclear membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Division of cytoplasm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Homologous pairing","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Replication","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19538,"text":"Which of the following structure forms the skeleton of the fetus?","explanation":"During fetal development, the structure that forms the basis of the skeletal system is **hyaline cartilage**. This remarkable tissue serves as a template for the future bones of the body, playing a pivotal role in shaping the initial skeleton of the fetus.\r\n\r\nHyaline cartilage is a type of connective tissue characterized by its translucent, glassy appearance. It provides a flexible yet supportive framework for the developing bones. In the early stages of embryonic life, most of the skeleton is primarily composed of hyaline cartilage. Over time, this cartilage undergoes a process called endochondral ossification, where it gradually transforms into bone tissue.\r\n\r\nAs the fetus grows, the hyaline cartilage is gradually replaced by true bone tissue, resulting in the formation of the bones of the body. This process continues well into postnatal life, contributing to the growth and development of the skeletal system.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 147.","responses":[{"text":"Compact bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrocartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spongy bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyaline cartilage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Elastic cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19539,"text":"During observing an embryological OSPE exam, the student identifies the process of gastrulation. Which process marks its commencement?","explanation":"Gastrulation, a fundamental process in embryonic development, is marked by the commencement of the **primitive streak**. This significant event sets in motion the transformation of the single-layered blastula into a more complex three-layered structure called the gastrula.\r\n\r\nThe primitive streak is a structure that forms on the surface of the developing embryo, typically along the midline. It represents the site where cells begin to migrate and reorganize to establish the three primary germ layers: ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm. These germ layers give rise to various tissues and organs in the developing embryo.\r\n\r\nAs gastrulation proceeds, cells from the epiblast layer migrate toward the primitive streak, move through it, and then distribute themselves into the developing germ layers. The precise organization and movement of cells during gastrulation are essential for the subsequent formation of tissues and organs and the overall body plan.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 59.","responses":[{"text":"Cardiogenic area","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Notochord","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primitive streak","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neural tube","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prechordal plate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19542,"text":"Which of the following hormone acts on the endometrium during the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle?","explanation":"During the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle, the hormone that primarily acts on the endometrium is **progesterone**. This phase follows ovulation when a mature follicle transforms into the corpus luteum, a temporary endocrine structure that secretes progesterone.\r\n\r\nProgesterone plays a critical role in preparing the uterine lining (endometrium) for possible implantation of a fertilized egg. It does so by inducing changes in the endometrial tissue, making it more receptive and suitable for the implantation process. These changes include thickening of the endometrium, increased vascularity, and the secretion of nutrients and factors necessary for early embryonic development.\r\n\r\nIf fertilization occurs, the corpus luteum continues to secrete progesterone, maintaining the uterine environment necessary for the early stages of pregnancy. If fertilization does not occur, the corpus luteum regresses, progesterone levels drop, and this triggers the shedding of the endometrial lining, resulting in menstruation.","reference":"Thiyagarajan DK, Basit H, Jeanmonod R. Physiology, menstrual cycle. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed September 18, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK500020/","responses":[{"text":"Estrogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Luteinizing hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicle stimulating hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progesterone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Androgen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19543,"text":"The hormone responsible for the development of secondary sexual character in females is released and distributed from which of the following cells?","explanation":"The development of secondary sexual characteristics in females is a finely tuned process regulated by hormones. One of the key hormones responsible for this development is **estrogen**, and it is primarily produced and distributed by the **granulosa cells**.\r\n\r\nGranulosa cells are an integral part of the ovarian follicles, where they surround and nurture the developing oocyte (egg). As the follicle matures, these granulosa cells become more specialized and produce increasing amounts of estrogen. Estrogen plays a pivotal role in shaping secondary sexual characteristics in females, such as breast development, regulation of the menstrual cycle, and the development of a more feminine physique.\r\n\r\nThe secretion of estrogen from granulosa cells is tightly regulated and is under the influence of pituitary hormones like follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH). When the granulosa cells receive the appropriate signals, they respond by producing and releasing estrogen into the bloodstream.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 34.","responses":[{"text":"Corona radiata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cumulus oophorous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Theca cells of growing follicle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulosa cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Antrum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19556,"text":"Sensory nerve signals from the moving parts apprise the brain of whether the movement is performed correctly. If not, the brain corrects it the next time movement is required. What is the name of this process?","explanation":"The process described, where sensory nerve signals from moving body parts inform the brain about the correctness of a movement and allow for adjustments, is known as **adaptive control**. \r\n\r\nAdaptive control is a crucial mechanism that underlies our ability to perform precise and coordinated movements. It relies on sensory feedback, often referred to as proprioception, which includes information from proprioceptors in muscles, tendons, and joints. These proprioceptive signals provide the brain with constant updates about the position, tension, and movement of body parts.\r\n\r\nWhen a movement is executed, sensory feedback helps the brain evaluate the outcome. If the movement is not performed correctly or needs adjustment, the brain makes real-time corrections. This process is essential for tasks ranging from simple activities like walking and reaching for objects to complex actions like playing a musical instrument or typing on a keyboard.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 10.","responses":[{"text":"Stimulus enhancement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rapid feedback mechanism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rapid negative feedback mechanism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive feedback mechanism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adaptive control","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19568,"text":"During a marathon race of 10km distance, an athlete requires which of the following organelles abundantly in muscle fibers?","explanation":"In a demanding physical activity like running a marathon, muscle cells require an abundant supply of energy to sustain prolonged exertion. The organelle that takes center stage in providing this energy is the **mitochondria**.\r\n\r\nMitochondria are often referred to as the \"powerhouses\" of the cell because they are responsible for generating adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the primary energy currency of the cell. During a marathon race, muscle fibers need a constant and substantial supply of ATP to fuel muscle contractions and maintain endurance.\r\n\r\nThe process by which mitochondria produce ATP is known as oxidative phosphorylation, which occurs in the inner mitochondrial membrane. During this process, electrons are shuttled through a series of protein complexes, creating a proton gradient that drives ATP synthesis.","reference":"Muscle mitochondria may form energy power grid. National Institutes of Health (NIH). Published August 13, 2015. Accessed September 18, 2023. https://www.nih.gov/news-events/nih-research-matters/muscle-mitochondria-may-form-energy-power-grid","responses":[{"text":"Vesicles with glycogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroxisome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribosome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitochondria","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19573,"text":"A person consumes alcohol in high quantity. Which of the following organelles are active in the liver to combat the toxic effect of the alcohol?","explanation":"When a person consumes alcohol in high quantities, the liver plays a crucial role in metabolizing and detoxifying this substance. One of the key organelles involved in this process is the **peroxisome**.\r\n\r\nPeroxisomes are specialized cellular structures that contain enzymes capable of metabolizing a variety of substances, including alcohol (ethanol). Specifically, **alcohol dehydrogenase**, an enzyme present in peroxisomes, begins the process of breaking down ethanol into acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is then further metabolized into acetate by another enzyme, aldehyde dehydrogenase.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020.","responses":[{"text":"Peroxisome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Golgi apparatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysosome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribosome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19574,"text":"Myocardial ischemia triggers coronary endothelial cells to release nitric oxide. In response, nitric oxide will activate which of the following second messenger?","explanation":"In myocardial ischemia, where the heart muscle is not receiving enough oxygen-rich blood, coronary endothelial cells play a critical role in responding to this challenge. One of the key responses is the release of **nitric oxide (NO)**.\r\n\r\nNitric oxide acts as a signaling molecule and is involved in vasodilation, which helps increase blood flow to the ischemic tissue, including the heart muscle. When nitric oxide is released by the endothelial cells, it activates a second messenger system, and in this case, the second messenger is **cyclic guanosine monophosphate (cGMP)**.\r\n\r\ncGMP serves as a key mediator in the signaling pathway initiated by nitric oxide. It activates various downstream effectors, including protein kinases and ion channels, leading to smooth muscle relaxation, vasodilation, and increased blood flow to the myocardial tissue affected by ischemia. This improved blood flow can help alleviate the symptoms associated with myocardial ischemia and protect the heart muscle from damage.","reference":"Murad F. Nitric oxide: the coming of the second messenger. Rambam Maimonides Medical Journal. Published April 30, 2011. Accessed September 18, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3678935/","responses":[{"text":"cAMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DAG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"cGMP","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ca","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IP3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19575,"text":"A person consumes alcohol in high quantity. Which of the following organelles is active in the liver to combat the toxic effect of the alcohol?","explanation":"When a person consumes alcohol in high quantities, the liver plays a crucial role in metabolizing and detoxifying this substance. One of the key organelles involved in this process is the **peroxisome**.\r\n\r\nPeroxisomes are specialized cellular structures that contain enzymes capable of metabolizing a variety of substances, including alcohol (ethanol). Specifically, **alcohol dehydrogenase**, an enzyme present in peroxisomes, begins the process of breaking down ethanol into acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is then further metabolized into acetate by another enzyme, aldehyde dehydrogenase.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 18.","responses":[{"text":"Endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribosome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Golgi apparatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysosome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroxisome","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19626,"text":"An increase in which of the following decreases the rate of diffusion across the cell membrane?","explanation":"The rate of diffusion across a cell membrane is influenced by several factors, and one of these crucial factors is the thickness of the membrane itself. When we talk about the cell membrane's thickness, we refer to the distance that molecules must traverse when moving from one side of the membrane to the other.\r\n\r\nAs a general rule, an increase in membrane thickness decreases the rate of diffusion. This is because a thicker membrane presents a greater physical barrier to the movement of molecules. Think of it like trying to walk through a narrow doorway versus a wide hallway—the wider hallway allows for faster movement.\r\n\r\nThe cell membrane is primarily composed of a **lipid bilayer**, which consists of two layers of lipid molecules. The thickness of this lipid bilayer can vary among different types of cells and organisms. In addition to the lipid bilayer, proteins and other molecules can also contribute to membrane thickness.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 512-513.","responses":[{"text":"Lipid solubility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Concentration gradient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thickness","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Temperature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Surface area","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19673,"text":"Sodium-potassium ATPase functions to pump the which of following ions inside and outside the cell?","explanation":"The sodium-potassium ATPase, also known as the sodium-potassium pump or Na+/K+ pump, is a critical membrane protein found in the plasma membrane of virtually all animal cells. Its primary function is to actively transport ions across the cell membrane, creating and maintaining an essential ion gradient that is crucial for various cellular processes.\r\n\r\nThe sodium-potassium ATPase pumps **three sodium ions (Na+)** out of the cell's interior and simultaneously pumps **two potassium ions (K+)** into the cell. This transport mechanism is an example of active transport, as it requires energy in the form of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to move ions against their concentration gradients.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 59.","responses":[{"text":"3 Na+ ions out and 2 K+ ions in","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"3 Na+ ions out and 3 K+ ions in","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 Na+ ions in and 3 K+ ions out","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 Na+ ions out and 3 K+ ions in","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3 Na+ ions in and 2 K+ ions out","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19752,"text":"Which mucopolysaccharide accumulates due to the deficiency of iduronate sulfatase in Hunter's disease?","explanation":"In Hunter's disease, a rare genetic disorder known as a mucopolysaccharidosis, there is a deficiency of the enzyme **iduronate sulfatase**. This enzyme is essential for the degradation of certain mucopolysaccharides, specifically **dermatan sulfate** and **heparan sulfate**, within lysosomes. Without functional iduronate sulfatase, these mucopolysaccharides accumulate in the body.\r\n\r\nDermatan sulfate is a linear polysaccharide composed of repeating disaccharide units and is a normal component of connective tissues and skin.\r\n\r\nThis pathological accumulation of dermatan sulfate in various tissues and organs contributes to the clinical features of Hunter's disease, including joint stiffness, facial coarseness, and organ dysfunction.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 164.","responses":[{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyaluronic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dermatan sulphate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Keratan sulphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chondroitin sulphate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19753,"text":"Which type of glycosidic linkage is present in cellulose that cannot be digested with amylase present in saliva and pancreatic juice?","explanation":"Cellulose is a complex carbohydrate and a major structural component of plant cell walls. What sets cellulose apart from other carbohydrates, particularly in terms of human digestion, is the type of glycosidic linkage it contains. Cellulose is primarily composed of glucose units linked together by **beta 1-4 glycosidic linkages**.\r\n\r\nThe critical distinction lies in the orientation of the glycosidic bond. In cellulose, the glucose molecules are linked in a **beta (β)** configuration, where the hydroxyl (-OH) groups on the first carbon atoms of adjacent glucose units point in opposite directions. This results in a linear and extended chain structure.\r\n\r\nHuman digestive enzymes, including amylase found in saliva and pancreatic juice, are primarily designed to break down carbohydrates with **alpha (α)** glycosidic linkages, as seen in starch and glycogen. These enzymes cleave the glycosidic bonds between glucose units with **alpha 1-4 glycosidic linkages**.\r\n\r\nBecause cellulose contains **beta 1-4 glycosidic linkages**, our digestive enzymes, including amylase, are ineffective at breaking these bonds. As a result, cellulose remains largely indigestible in the human digestive system.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 86.","responses":[{"text":"Beta 1-6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha 1-3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha 1-4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta 1-3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta 1-4","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19755,"text":"Proteoglycans are conjugated proteins that contain carbohydrates in which form?","explanation":"Proteoglycans are a unique class of conjugated proteins found in the extracellular matrix and various connective tissues of the body. These molecules have a distinctive composition, as they contain carbohydrates in the form of **glycosaminoglycans (GAGs)**.\r\n\r\n**Glycosaminoglycans** are long, unbranched polysaccharide chains composed of repeating disaccharide units. These units typically consist of an amino sugar (either glucosamine or galactosamine) and an uronic acid (either glucuronic acid or iduronic acid). GAGs are characterized by their high negative charge due to the presence of sulfate groups, making them highly hydrophilic.\r\n\r\nIn the context of proteoglycans, GAGs are covalently attached to a protein core, forming large macromolecular complexes. This combination of proteins and GAGs gives proteoglycans their unique properties, such as the ability to bind water and provide structural support to tissues.","reference":"Rodwell VW, Bender DA, Botham KM, Kennelly PJ, Weil PA. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 147.","responses":[{"text":"Cellulose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dextran","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycosaminoglycan","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Maltotriose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycogen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19757,"text":"Which repeating disaccharide units make the anticoagulant polymer heparin?","explanation":"Heparin, a potent anticoagulant, is a complex polysaccharide composed of repeating disaccharide units. These repeating units are primarily made up of **D-glucosamine** and **L-iduronic acid**.\r\n\r\nThese repeating disaccharide units are connected in a specific manner to form the heparin molecule, and it is this distinct structure that underlies heparin's anticoagulant function.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 159.","responses":[{"text":"N-Acetyl-D-galactosamine and  D-glucuronic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"L-iduronic acid and N-acetyl galactosamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"N-acetyl glucosamine and D-glucuronic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"D-glucosamine and L-iduronic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"L-iduronic acid and N-acetyl galactosamine sulphate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19758,"text":"Which secondary structure is characterized by a single, spiral chain of amino acids and is stabilized by hydrogen bonds?","explanation":"The **alpha helix** is a notable secondary structure in proteins, characterized by a single, spiral chain of amino acids. This distinct helical conformation is primarily stabilized by a particular type of intermolecular bond known as **hydrogen bonds**.\r\n\r\nIn this structure, the polypeptide chain winds around a central axis, forming a helical or coil-like arrangement. What makes the alpha helix especially stable is the presence of hydrogen bonds between specific atoms within the amino acids along the chain.\r\n\r\nThese hydrogen bonds form between the carbonyl oxygen atom of one amino acid and the amide hydrogen atom of an amino acid that is further along the chain. This bonding pattern repeats, with each turn of the helix typically encompassing about 3.6 amino acid residues.\r\n\r\nThe alpha helix is known for its compact, tightly packed structure, with the side chains of amino acids extending outward from the central helical axis. This unique conformation sets it apart from other secondary structures.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 16.","responses":[{"text":"Alpha helix","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ω-loop","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bend","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"β-pleated sheet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"U-turn","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19762,"text":"Which amino acid has both glucogenic and ketogenic metabolic properties?","explanation":"Among the 20 standard amino acids that serve as the building blocks of proteins, **tryptophan** stands out as a unique amino acid with both **glucogenic and ketogenic** metabolic properties.\r\n\r\n1. **Glucogenic Property:** Tryptophan can be metabolized into intermediates of the **gluconeogenesis pathway**. In other words, its breakdown can yield molecules that can be converted into glucose through various metabolic reactions. This property makes tryptophan a source of carbon for glucose synthesis.\r\n\r\n2. **Ketogenic Property:** Additionally, tryptophan can also be metabolized into ketone bodies, such as **acetoacetate and beta-hydroxybutyrate**. These ketone bodies can serve as an alternative energy source, particularly for tissues like the brain and heart during periods of fasting or low carbohydrate intake.","reference":"Teodósio R, Aragão C, Conceição LEC, Dias J, Engrola S. Metabolic fate is defined by amino acid nature in gilthead seabream fed different diet formulations. Animals : an Open Access Journal from MDPI. Published July 2, 2022. Accessed September 22, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9264960/","responses":[{"text":"Tryptophan","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspartate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histidine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19765,"text":"In quaternary structure, cysteine residues interact with the other polypeptide chains with the help of which of the following bonds?","explanation":"**Quaternary structure** involves the arrangement and interaction of multiple polypeptide chains (subunits) to form a functional protein. Within this intricate structure, **disulfide bridges** play a pivotal role in stabilizing the quaternary configuration.\r\n\r\nDisulfide bridges are covalent bonds formed between cysteine residues. These bonds, also known as disulfide bonds or disulfide bridges (S-S bonds), are strong and covalent in nature. They contribute significantly to the stability of the protein's overall structure.\r\n\r\nIn proteins composed of multiple subunits, disulfide bridges can occur within the same polypeptide chain (intrachain) or between different chains (interchain). Regardless of their location, these bridges act as molecular \"stitches,\" ensuring the proper assembly of the functional protein. Moreover, disulfide bridges strengthen the quaternary structure by maintaining the three-dimensional arrangement of subunits.","reference":"Meitzler JL, Hinde S, Bánfi B, Nauseef WM, Ortiz de Montellano PR. Conserved cysteine residues provide a protein-protein interaction surface in dual oxidase (Duox) proteins. The Journal of Biological Chemistry. Published March 8, 2013. Accessed September 22, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3591624/","responses":[{"text":"Hydrophobic interactions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disulfide bridges","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Van der Waal forces","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Covalent interactions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrogen bonding","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19831,"text":"Emulsification of fats is a process in which large complex fat globules get converted into smaller fat molecules. Which emulsifying agent is present in the gastrointestinal tract for the digestion of fats?","explanation":"**Bile salts** are pivotal in the gastrointestinal tract for emulsifying fats, breaking large fat globules into smaller molecules to aid digestion and absorption.\r\n\r\n**Emulsification:** Bile salts, with hydrophobic and hydrophilic regions, surround and solubilize fat droplets in the small intestine, increasing their surface area for better enzyme access.\r\n\r\n**Enhanced Digestion:** Smaller fat droplets are efficiently broken down by enzymes like pancreatic lipase into fatty acids and glycerol, promoting absorption.\r\n\r\n**Micelle Formation:** Bile salts assist in forming micelles that transport lipid products for absorption by enterocytes.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 175.","responses":[{"text":"Biliverdin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilirubin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic lipase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bile salts","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric lipase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19832,"text":"A patient came to the outpatient department with a condition that causes a dark, sometimes scaly rash to develop on skin areas exposed to sunlight. He also complained of bright redness of the tongue and constipation/diarrhea. Which deficiency causes this condition?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms, including a dark, scaly rash on sun-exposed skin, a bright red tongue, and gastrointestinal issues like constipation and diarrhea, indicate **pellagra**—a condition caused by a deficiency of **niacin** (vitamin B3).\r\n\r\n1. **Skin Rash:** Niacin is essential for healthy skin. Its deficiency leads to the characteristic rash on sun-exposed areas.\r\n\r\n2. **Bright Red Tongue:** Glossitis, a bright red tongue, is common in pellagra due to niacin deficiency.\r\n\r\n3. **Gastrointestinal Issues:** Pellagra can affect the gastrointestinal tract, causing symptoms like constipation and diarrhea.","reference":"Redzic S, Hashmi MF, Gupta V. Niacin deficiency. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed September 24, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557728/","responses":[{"text":"Thiamin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Niacin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyridoxine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pantothenic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19833,"text":"Epimers are carbohydrates that vary in one position for the placement of the OH group. Which of the following is an example of an epimer?","explanation":"Epimers are a type of stereoisomer, specifically diastereomers, where two molecules have the same molecular formula but differ in the configuration of a single chiral carbon atom. In carbohydrates, chiral carbons often result from the presence of multiple hydroxyl (OH) groups. In the case of glucose and galactose, they are considered epimers because they differ in the spatial arrangement of hydroxyl groups at the C-4 position.\r\n\r\nIn **glucose**, the OH group at the C-4 position is oriented in the \"downward\" direction (in Fischer projection), while in **galactose**, it is oriented in the \"upward\" direction. This single difference in the placement of the OH group at C-4 distinguishes glucose from galactose, making them epimers of each other.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 84.","responses":[{"text":"Glucose and ribose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mannose and ribulose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose and fructose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Xylose and glucose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose and galactose","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19834,"text":"Which of the following describes the process by which mRNA synthesis is initiated, elongated, and terminated?","explanation":"The process by which mRNA synthesis is initiated, elongated, and terminated is known as **transcription**. Transcription is a fundamental cellular process that takes place in the nucleus of eukaryotic cells and in the cytoplasm of prokaryotic cells. Here's how transcription works:\r\n\r\n1. **Initiation:** Transcription begins with the binding of RNA polymerase to the promoter region of a gene on the DNA template strand. This marks the start site for mRNA synthesis.\r\n\r\n2. **Elongation:** RNA polymerase moves along the DNA template strand, catalyzing the addition of complementary ribonucleotides (A, U, C, and G) to form the mRNA molecule. The mRNA strand is elongated in the 5' to 3' direction, complementary to the DNA template strand.\r\n\r\n3. **Termination:** Transcription concludes when RNA polymerase reaches a termination signal on the DNA template strand. This signal causes RNA polymerase to detach from the DNA, and the newly synthesized mRNA is released.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 435.","responses":[{"text":"Translation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Replication","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splicing","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transcription","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transformation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19835,"text":"Which of the following is caused by the deficiency of vitamin D?","explanation":"**Rickets** is a condition that is **caused by the deficiency of vitamin D**. It primarily affects children and is characterized by the improper mineralization of bones, leading to bone deformities and weakness. Here's how vitamin D deficiency contributes to the development of rickets:\r\n\r\nVitamin D plays a crucial role in calcium absorption in the intestines. When there is a deficiency of vitamin D, the body is unable to absorb sufficient calcium from the diet. This leads to low levels of calcium in the blood.\r\n\r\nIn response to low blood calcium levels, the body tries to maintain normal calcium levels by mobilizing calcium from the bones. However, the constant removal of calcium weakens the bones, making them prone to deformities.\r\n\r\nCommon symptoms of rickets include bowed legs, delayed growth, and muscle weakness. It is a preventable condition through adequate exposure to sunlight (which stimulates vitamin D synthesis in the skin) and dietary sources of vitamin D.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 392.","responses":[{"text":"Beriberi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rickets","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Parkinson","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scurvy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dementia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19836,"text":"A 20-year-old boy mistakenly infused a one-liter extra amount of 0.9% NaCl solution. What will be the intermediate effect of this infusion on his body fluid compartment?","explanation":"Infusing an additional one liter of 0.9% NaCl solution will lead to an **increase in the extracellular fluid (ECF)** compartment.  0.9% NaCl is isotonic to body fluids, meaning it has the same osmolarity as normal extracellular fluid. When infused, this solution will distribute throughout the ECF, expanding it. The excess volume introduced into the ECF will temporarily increase its volume.\r\n\r\nThe intracellular fluid (ICF), on the other hand, remains largely unaffected initially because the solution's osmolarity matches that of the ECF. Therefore, water does not shift between the ICF and ECF to maintain osmotic balance.\r\n\r\nHowever, over time, the body's regulatory mechanisms will come into play. Excess ECF will lead to increased excretion of salt and water by the kidneys, eventually returning the ECF volume to its normal range. In the process, some of the excess fluid from the ECF may shift into the ICF, but this is a gradual adjustment.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 311.","responses":[{"text":"Decrease in ECF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in ICF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ECF will remain same","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in ECF","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decrease in ICF","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19837,"text":"A football player from Lyari, while playing in excessively hot weather, felt dizzy and was brought to the hospital. On examination, he was found to be dehydrated, his blood pressure was low (70/50), and his pulse rate was high (110 b/min). Which of the following explains the patient's condition?","explanation":"The football player's symptoms, including dizziness, dehydration, low blood pressure (70/50), and a high pulse rate (110 b/min), are indicative of a condition known as **hyperosmotic volume contraction**.\r\n\r\nIn hyperosmotic volume contraction, there is a loss of water and solutes from the extracellular fluid (ECF) without a proportionate loss of water from the intracellular fluid (ICF). This results in an increase in the osmolarity (concentration of solutes) of the ECF. The elevated osmolarity draws water from the cells into the ECF, leading to cellular dehydration.\r\n\r\nThe low blood pressure is a consequence of reduced blood volume due to dehydration, and the high pulse rate is the body's compensatory mechanism to maintain blood flow to vital organs in response to low blood pressure.","reference":"(1) Villiger M, Stoop R, Vetsch T, et al. Evaluation and review of body fluids saliva, sweat and tear compared to biochemical hydration assessment markers within blood and urine. European Journal of Clinical Nutrition. Published January 2018. Accessed September 25, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5765170/\r\n\r\n(2) Dow Lecture slides: Foundation module, physiology, body fluid compartments.","responses":[{"text":"Hyper osmotic volume contraction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypotonic ECF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertonic ICF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypo osmotic volume contraction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isotonic ICF","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19882,"text":"A patient was admitted with severe substernal chest pain of 4-hour duration. His lab tests revealed an increased level of serum creatine kinase. Which of the following conditions causes this increase?","explanation":"Elevated levels of serum creatine kinase (CK) are often indicative of **damage to the plasma membrane** of muscle cells, including cardiac muscle cells in the heart. In this patient's case, the severe substernal chest pain and increased serum CK levels suggest myocardial injury, commonly seen in conditions like myocardial infarction (heart attack).\r\n\r\nWhen the plasma membrane of muscle cells, especially cardiac myocytes, is damaged due to ischemia or other factors, intracellular enzymes like CK are released into the bloodstream. CK is abundant in cardiac muscle, and its elevated levels in the blood serve as a valuable marker for cardiac muscle injury.","reference":"Cabaniss CD, Walker HK, Hall WD, Hurst JW. Creatine kinase. Clinical Methods: The History, Physical, and Laboratory Examinations. Published 1990. Accessed September 27, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK352/","responses":[{"text":"Damage to the plasma membrane","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased Golgi activity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nuclear lysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitochondrial swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased endoplasmic activity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19883,"text":"You are asked to review a liver biopsy from a patient with a history of alcohol abuse. Which of the following pathological changes will most likely lead to the death of hepatocytes and liver cirrhosis?","explanation":"**Bridging necrosis in hepatocytes** leads to the death of hepatocytes and the development of liver cirrhosis, especially in the context of alcohol abuse.\r\n\r\nBridging necrosis is a severe form of hepatocyte injury characterized by the presence of continuous areas of necrosis that connect adjacent portal areas or central veins within the liver lobule. This extensive and continuous necrosis disrupts the normal liver architecture and can result in the formation of fibrous bridges, leading to the development of cirrhosis over time.\r\n\r\nIn the case of alcohol abuse, chronic and repeated liver injury, including bridging necrosis, can ultimately progress to cirrhosis, which is characterized by extensive fibrosis and the loss of normal liver function.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 843.\r\n\r\n(2) MALHI H, GUICCIARDI ME, GORES GJ. Hepatocyte death: a clear and present danger. Physiological reviews. Published July 2010. Accessed September 27, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2943859/","responses":[{"text":"Fatty changes in liver cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Karyolysis in hepatocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bridging necrosis in hepatocytes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydropic change of hepatocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycogen deposition in hepatocyte nuclei","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19884,"text":"A patient suffers a stroke and has left-sided weakness and paralysis in the upper extremity. Which type of necrosis is associated with a well-developed infarct of the brain?","explanation":"In the context of a stroke, particularly in the brain, a well-developed infarct typically leads to **liquefactive necrosis**. Liquefactive necrosis is characterized by the transformation of tissue into a liquid, resembling the consistency of pus. It is often observed in the central nervous system, including the brain, when there is an ischemic injury, as seen in a stroke.\r\n\r\nDuring a stroke, a lack of blood supply to a specific area of the brain causes cell death. In the brain, tissue tends to break down rapidly, resulting in liquefactive necrosis. The affected area becomes soft and appears as a fluid-filled cyst, as the tissue is replaced by a liquid-filled cavity.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 43.","responses":[{"text":"Liquefactive","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Enzymatic fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gangrenous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coagulative","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caseous","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19932,"text":"Enveloped viruses are sensitive to desiccation and are mostly transmitted through the body fluids. From where do these viruses derive their envelopes from?","explanation":"Enveloped viruses are characterized by their outer lipid bilayer, known as the envelope. This envelope is crucial for the virus's structure and function. One of the primary sources from which these viruses derive their envelopes is the **plasma membrane** of the host cell.\r\n\r\nDuring the replication cycle of enveloped viruses, they acquire their envelopes as they bud through the host cell's plasma membrane. As new viral particles are formed, they take a piece of the host cell's membrane with them, encapsulating themselves in this lipid bilayer. This process allows enveloped viruses to be sensitive to desiccation and primarily transmitted through body fluids, as their lipid envelopes are vulnerable to drying out and disruption.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 222.","responses":[{"text":"Plasma membrane","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysosomes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Golgi bodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribosomes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19933,"text":"Some viruses are defective and need another virus to help replicate. Which of the following is an example of these viruses?","explanation":"**Hepatitis D** (HDV) stands as a prime example of a **defective virus** that relies on another virus for replication. Hepatitis D is unique because it can only infect individuals who are already infected with Hepatitis B. It is classified as a \"defective\" or \"incomplete\" virus because it lacks the capability to produce its envelope proteins independently. Instead, it utilizes the envelope proteins provided by hepatitis B virus (HBV) to form new viral particles.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 247.","responses":[{"text":"Influenza","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dengue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis D","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mumps","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19934,"text":"Which of the following statements is correct regarding metastatic calcification?","explanation":"Metastatic calcification is a pathological process characterized by the deposition of calcium salts in various tissues throughout the body due to elevated blood calcium levels. Among the provided statements, the **correct** one regarding metastatic calcification is that it **occurs in thyroid papilloma**.\r\n\r\nThyroid papilloma, a type of thyroid tumor, can indeed serve as a site for the deposition of calcium salts when there is hypercalcemia (high blood calcium levels). This occurrence is an example of metastatic calcification, where calcium precipitates and accumulates in tissues.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 65.","responses":[{"text":"Mitochondria is involved in early stages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Occurs in thyroid papilloma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium level is normal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Occurs in dead and dying tissues","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Occurs in damaged heart valves","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19937,"text":"Regarding apoptosis which pair is matched correctly?","explanation":"In the context of apoptosis, the correct match is **BH1-3 proteins** associated with **triggering apoptosis**. These Bcl-2 family proteins promote cell survival by preventing apoptosis. They do so by inhibiting pro-apoptotic Bax and Bak proteins. Therefore, the presence of BH1-3 proteins generally suppresses apoptosis, which is contrary to the other options.\r\n\r\nThe other options are incorrectly matched. The intrinsic pathway primarily activates caspase 9, not caspases 8 and 10. The RAS gene is generally associated with cell growth and proliferation but not the activation of apoptosis. There is no specific term like \"BH1-4 proteins\" associated with apoptosis. BH3-only proteins are, in fact, promoters of apoptosis by interacting with pro-apoptotic and anti-apoptotic Bcl-2 family members.","reference":"Lomonosova E, Chinnadurai G. BH3-only proteins in apoptosis and beyond: an overview. Oncogene. Published December 2008. Accessed September 28, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2928556/","responses":[{"text":"BH1-3 proteins - trigger apoptosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"RAS gene - activates apoptosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BH1-4 proteins - trigger apoptosis 3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BH3 only proteins - inhibitors of apoptosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrinsic pathway - activates caspases 8 and 10","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19938,"text":"What is it called when a specific infection is persistent, usually at a low level in a certain geographical area?","explanation":"When a specific infection persists at a **low level in a certain geographical area**, it is referred to as an **endemic** disease. Endemic infections are characterized by their continuous presence within a particular region or population without causing widespread outbreaks.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, an **epidemic** occurs when a disease suddenly spreads rapidly and affects a larger number of individuals within a defined population or area. Epidemics are often characterized by a surge in the number of cases well above the expected baseline.\r\n\r\n**Sporadic** refers to isolated or occasional cases that occur irregularly and are not connected to a specific pattern or geography.\r\n\r\n**Pandemic** is a term used to describe a global outbreak of a disease that affects a wide geographic area, often crossing national borders.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 32.","responses":[{"text":"Pandemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endemic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporadic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High infective region","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19939,"text":"Toxic shock syndrome caused by exotoxin directly binds to class II MHC protein and T-cell receptor. Which of the following organisms is responsible for this disease?","explanation":"Toxic shock syndrome (TSS) is a severe condition primarily caused by the exotoxin produced by ***Staphylococcus aureus***. This exotoxin, known as toxic shock syndrome toxin-1 (TSST-1), plays a pivotal role in TSS pathogenesis. TSST-1 has a unique ability to directly bind to both the class II major histocompatibility complex (MHC) protein on antigen-presenting cells and the T-cell receptor on T cells. TSST-1 acts as a **superantigen**, leading to a massive release of proinflammatory cytokines and causing the characteristic symptoms of TSS.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 111.","responses":[{"text":"Staphylococcus saprophyticus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus epidermidis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus haemolyticus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pyogenes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19940,"text":"Through which of the following ways are gastrointestinal tract diseases commonly transmitted in a human?","explanation":"Gastrointestinal tract diseases are commonly transmitted in humans through various routes, but one of the most common modes is **food or water**. Contaminated food and water sources can harbor pathogenic microorganisms, such as bacteria, viruses, and parasites, which, when ingested, can lead to gastrointestinal infections. This route of transmission is particularly significant in cases of foodborne and waterborne illnesses.\r\n\r\nWhile indirect and direct human-to-human contact can also contribute to disease transmission, these modes are often more relevant for respiratory or skin-to-skin infections rather than gastrointestinal diseases. Bloodborne transmission typically relates to diseases such as hepatitis and HIV, which are not primarily associated with the gastrointestinal tract. Transplacental transmission, on the other hand, is more relevant to the vertical transmission of infections from mother to fetus and is not a common route for gastrointestinal diseases.","reference":"Burd EM, Hinrichs BH. Gastrointestinal infections. Molecular Pathology in Clinical Practice. Published May 19, 2015. Accessed September 28, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7123654/","responses":[{"text":"Food or water","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Direct human to human contact","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trans placental","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indirect human to human contact","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood borne","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19950,"text":"Which of the following statements best corresponds to transposons?","explanation":"Transposons are **short sequences of DNA** known for their ability to move or transpose within a genome. One of their prominent features is their role in carrying **antibiotic-resistant genes**. Transposons play a significant role in the spread of antibiotic resistance among bacteria by enabling the transfer of resistance genes between different genomic locations.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 10.","responses":[{"text":"Short sequences of transfer RNA required for mutation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Required for enzyme degradation during replication","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short sequences of DNA contain mutation genes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short sequences of DNA contain regulatory genes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short sequences of DNA contain antibiotic-resistant genes","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19951,"text":"Which plasmid makes the bacterial cell develop resistance against some specific antibiotics?","explanation":"Among various plasmids found in bacterial cells, the one responsible for conferring resistance against specific antibiotics is the **R plasmid**. This plasmid carries genes encoding resistance mechanisms, such as antibiotic-degrading enzymes or efflux pumps. Bacteria containing R plasmids are equipped with the ability to survive and multiply in the presence of antibiotics that would otherwise be lethal.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 87.","responses":[{"text":"Col plasmid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"F plasmid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Degradative plasmid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"R plasmid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Virulence plasmid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19952,"text":"What is the function of flagella in a bacterial cell?","explanation":"Flagella in bacterial cells primarily serve the function of **locomotion**. These slender whip-like appendages enable bacteria to move towards favorable environments or away from harmful ones, contributing significantly to their survival and proliferation.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2020: 11.","responses":[{"text":"Locomotion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reproduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acts as a sex pili","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrive in nutrient agar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adhere to tissue surfaces","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19953,"text":"What is a cluster of polar flagella in a bacterial cell known as?","explanation":"A cluster of polar flagella in a bacterial cell is known as **lophotrichous**. This arrangement consists of multiple flagella emerging from one or both ends of the bacterial cell. The term \"polar\" indicates that the flagella are located at one or both poles (ends) of the cell. Lophotrichous flagella provide the bacterium with the ability to move efficiently in a specific direction, typically through rotational movements that propel the cell forward or backward. This flagellar arrangement is one of several variations seen in bacterial species, each adapted to their specific locomotion needs.","reference":"Park J, Kim Y, Lee W, Lim S. Modeling of lophotrichous bacteria reveals key factors for swimming reorientation. Scientific Reports. Published April 20, 2022. Accessed September 29, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9021275/","responses":[{"text":"Lophotrichous","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Peritrichous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amphitrichous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monotrichous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bipolar flagella","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19954,"text":"Decrease in which of the following increases the fluidity of the cell membrane?","explanation":"Cholesterol is a key determinant of cell membrane fluidity. Its decrease increases membrane fluidity by preventing excessive packing of fatty acid tails in colder temperatures and allowing greater movement in warmer conditions. Cholesterol acts like a \"temperature buffer,\" helping to maintain optimal membrane function across a range of temperatures. While reducing cholesterol can enhance fluidity, maintaining an appropriate balance is crucial for membrane integrity and function.","reference":"Zhang J, Li Q, Wu Y, et al. Cholesterol content in cell membrane maintains surface levels of ErbB2 and confers a therapeutic vulnerability in ErbB2-positive breast cancer. Cell Communication and Signaling : CCS. Published February 20, 2019. Accessed September 29, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6383291/","responses":[{"text":"Proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholesterol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phospholipids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphingosine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbohydrates","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20016,"text":"A 45-year-old patient is being administered a drug through a route that offers the most first-pass metabolism. Through which route is the drug most likely being administered?","explanation":"In this case, the drug is most likely being administered orally. **Oral administration** involves swallowing a drug, which then passes through the gastrointestinal tract before entering systemic circulation. This route often exhibits the most significant first-pass metabolism because the drug must pass through the liver (hepatic first-pass effect) and the gut wall.\r\n\r\nDuring hepatic first-pass metabolism, enzymes in the liver may metabolize the drug, reducing its bioavailability and altering its pharmacological properties. As a result, a smaller fraction of the drug reaches systemic circulation in its active form.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, other routes like **intramuscular, rectal, sublingual, and inhalation** generally bypass or have reduced exposure to the liver and gut wall, resulting in less first-pass metabolism. Therefore, for drugs requiring minimal first-pass metabolism, alternative routes of administration may be preferred over oral administration to achieve higher bioavailability and therapeutic efficacy.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 6.","responses":[{"text":"Oral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intramuscular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sublingual","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhalation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20021,"text":"A patient is given drug X to decrease the toxicity of heavy metal by directly binding to it and not allowing it to bind to tissues. Which of the following is an example of this kind of antagonism?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 17.","responses":[{"text":"Functional","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Allosteric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemical","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Irreversible","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pharmacokinetic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20030,"text":"Pakistan has a three-tier healthcare system organization. The first level of care provides primary healthcare services to people. Which of the following is the component of the first level of healthcare facilities of the three-tier system?","explanation":"In Pakistan's three-tier healthcare system, the first level of care is primarily responsible for providing primary healthcare services to the population. Within this level, one of the key components is the **Basic Health Unit (BHU)**. \r\n\r\nBasic Health Units are primary healthcare facilities that serve as the frontline of healthcare delivery in both rural and urban areas. They are typically staffed by healthcare professionals such as doctors, nurses, and paramedical staff. BHUs are essential in providing a range of basic healthcare services, including preventive care, immunizations, maternal and child health services, treatment of common illnesses, and health education to the local community.\r\n\r\nPrivate general practitioners can also be part of the first level of care, especially in urban areas, where they offer primary healthcare services in private clinics. However, BHUs are a more organized and government-sponsored component of the first level, aiming to reach underserved populations, particularly in rural areas.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Foundation, Community medicine, Healthcare delivery system in Pakistan.","responses":[{"text":"Informal sector","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"District headquarter hospital","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Private general practitioner","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basic health unit","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tehsil headquarter hospital","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20063,"text":"What term describes any abnormality or disruption in the normal structure or function of a body part, organ, or system, which is marked by a specific set of symptoms and signs, and whose underlying cause, nature, and outcome may be identified or unknown?","explanation":"The term that describes any abnormality or disruption in the normal structure or function of a body part, organ, or system, marked by a specific set of symptoms and signs, and whose underlying cause, nature, and outcome may be identified or unknown, is **\"disease.\"**\r\n\r\nDisease is a broad concept encompassing a wide range of health conditions that deviate from the normal state of well-being. It can manifest in various ways, such as through physical, biochemical, or functional abnormalities. Diseases can have identifiable causes, known pathophysiology, and predictable outcomes, or they may remain mysterious with unknown etiology and unpredictable outcomes.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Foundation, Community medicine, Topic name: Concept of disease and health.","responses":[{"text":"Infirmity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Illness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Health","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disease","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20064,"text":"After taking a high-protein meal, which of the following cellular organelles are most active in manufacturing pepsinogen in the stomach?","explanation":"The cellular organelle most active in manufacturing pepsinogen in the stomach after a high-protein meal is the **endoplasmic reticulum (ER).**\r\n\r\nPepsinogen is an inactive precursor of pepsin, an enzyme responsible for the initial digestion of proteins in the stomach. Pepsinogen is synthesized by chief cells in the gastric glands of the stomach. The chief cells contain a highly developed rough endoplasmic reticulum (RER), which is involved in protein synthesis.\r\n\r\nWhen you consume a high-protein meal, the body responds by increasing the production of digestive enzymes like pepsinogen to aid in protein digestion. The RER in chief cells becomes highly active, synthesizing pepsinogen molecules. These newly synthesized pepsinogen molecules are then packaged and transported to the gastric lumen via the Golgi apparatus for storage in zymogen granules.\r\n\r\nWhen needed for digestion, pepsinogen is converted into its active form, pepsin, by the acidic environment of the stomach. This conversion is crucial for breaking down dietary proteins into smaller peptides during digestion.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 312.","responses":[{"text":"Lysosome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroxisome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Golgi apparatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribosome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoplasmic reticulum","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":20065,"text":"Intracellular Ca2+ concentration greatly impacts the force of muscular contraction. Which of the following second messenger has a role in the release of Ca2+ from the sarcoplasmic reticulum?","explanation":"The release of calcium ions (Ca²⁺) from the sarcoplasmic reticulum is a crucial step in muscle contraction regulation. This process is mediated by the second messenger **IP₃ (inositol trisphosphate).**\r\n\r\nWhen a muscle cell receives a signal to contract, it initiates an action potential, leading to the release of acetylcholine at the neuromuscular junction. Acetylcholine binds to receptors on the muscle cell membrane, causing depolarization and the propagation of the action potential into the cell through the T-tubules. This action potential then activates voltage-gated receptors in the sarcoplasmic reticulum.\r\n\r\nThese receptors are known as dihydropyridine receptors (DHPRs), and they interact with ryanodine receptors (RyR) on the sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane. This interaction triggers the release of Ca²⁺ ions from the sarcoplasmic reticulum into the cytoplasm, where they bind to troponin on the thin filaments, initiating muscle contraction.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 924-925.","responses":[{"text":"Ca ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IP3","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"cGMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"cAMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DAG","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20066,"text":"Which of the following is the most abundant unsaturated fatty acid in membrane lipids?","explanation":"The most abundant unsaturated fatty acid in membrane lipids is **oleic acid.** Oleic acid is a monounsaturated fatty acid, meaning it has one double bond in its carbon chain. It is commonly found in various biological membranes, including cell membranes. This fatty acid plays a crucial role in maintaining membrane fluidity and flexibility.\r\n\r\nWhile other unsaturated fatty acids like linoleic acid and linolenic acid are also important for health and are components of membrane lipids, oleic acid tends to be the most prevalent in biological membranes. Its presence helps ensure that the lipid bilayer of cell membranes remains dynamic and responsive to changes in temperature and other environmental factors, allowing cells to function optimally. Additionally, oleic acid is often associated with various health benefits and is a common component of healthy dietary fats.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Foundation, Biochemistry, Topic name: Cell membrane.","responses":[{"text":"Linoleic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Linolenic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oleic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Palmitoleic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arachidonic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20081,"text":"A professor of public health was very popular amongst students. Her actions inspired others to dream more, learn more, do more, and become more. Which of the following best describes this definition according to John Quincy Adams?","explanation":"A leader is someone who inspires and motivates others to dream more, learn more, do more, and become more. They often serve as role models and set an example for others to follow. Leaders not only guide and teach but also empower individuals to reach their full potential. In the context of education, a professor who is popular among students and inspires them to excel is indeed acting as a leader. This professor is not merely an evaluator, teacher, manager, or supervisor, but rather someone who goes beyond these roles to instill enthusiasm, motivation, and a sense of purpose in their students, which is a hallmark of effective leadership.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Foundation, Community medicine, Topic: Leadership in healthcare.","responses":[{"text":"Manager","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Evaluator","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leader","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Teacher","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supervisor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20082,"text":"The nurse in charge was very strict in the administration and management of her ward in the hospital. She does not hesitate to complain to higher authorities about someone making a mistake but is also quite generous when someone does a good job. In this case, the nurse in charge has what type of power over others?","explanation":"In this case, the nurse in charge primarily wields **legitimate power** over others. Legitimate power is a form of social power derived from a person's formal position or authority within an organization or hierarchy. The nurse's role as the person in charge of the ward in the hospital gives her the legitimate authority to manage and make decisions concerning the ward's operations, including reporting mistakes or rewarding good performance. When she complains to higher authorities about mistakes, she is exercising her legitimate power to enforce rules and standards.\r\n\r\nWhile the nurse's behavior may also involve aspects of reward and potentially coercive power, the core source of her influence in this scenario is her official position, making it an example of legitimate power. This type of power is often linked to organizational structures and hierarchies and is essential for maintaining order and efficiency within healthcare settings.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Foundation, Community medicine, Topic name:  Leadership in healthcare.","responses":[{"text":"Coercive power","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reward power","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Legitimate power","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Referent power","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Expert power","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20083,"text":"While dealing with a case of intellectual disability, the father of a child wanted medical treatment for the child, while the mother thought that her child was having evil spirit effects and should be treated by faith healers. Being a culturally competent doctor, how would you deal with such a situation?","explanation":"As a culturally competent doctor, it's important to **respect the cultural values, norms, and rituals** of the patient and their family. In this situation, where the parents have differing views on treatment, the best approach is to facilitate open and respectful communication. Rather than denying one perspective, the doctor should provide medical information while acknowledging and respecting the family's cultural beliefs. Offering options and engaging in collaborative decision-making can lead to a more effective and respectful resolution.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Foundation, Community medicine, Topic name: Culture, cultural belief, and holistic care.","responses":[{"text":"Try to convince the mother that the father is right","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Being a culturally sensitive doctor, don't argue with them","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respect the cultural set values, norms, and rituals","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Let mother take her to faith healer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Straightforwardly deny the understanding of the mother","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20085,"text":"During an awareness talk about mental health issues and their treatment,  it was highlighted that mental illness should not be stigmatized and must be treated according to ethical principles. Hence, doctors should also treat their patients without any commercial benefit from the pharmaceutical companies because of the high regard of doctors in the community. Which of the following best describes this example?","explanation":"**Cultural values** are the deeply ingrained beliefs and principles held by a society or community. These values guide individuals' behaviors, interactions, and decisions within that culture. In this case, the emphasis on treating mental illness without any commercial benefit from pharmaceutical companies reflects a cultural value within the medical community and society at large.\r\n\r\nThe value placed on ethical principles and the avoidance of stigmatizing mental illness are indicative of the cultural norms and beliefs regarding healthcare and mental health. It signifies a collective understanding that prioritizes patient well-being over financial gain and recognizes the importance of addressing mental health issues without discrimination.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Foundation, Behavior sciences, Topic name: Delivery of culturally relevant practice.","responses":[{"text":"Culture values","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cultural belief","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cultural relativism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cultural norms","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cultural attitude","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20102,"text":"If red blood cells are placed in a solution containing 0.3% NaCl, what will be the effect on them?","explanation":"If red blood cells (RBCs) are placed in a solution containing 0.3% NaCl, it would be considered a **hypotonic** solution. In a hypotonic solution, the concentration of solutes is lower outside the RBCs compared to the inside.\r\n\r\nThe effect on RBCs placed in a hypotonic solution like 0.3% NaCl would be **bursting** or **lysis**. This happens because water moves into the RBCs from the surrounding solution due to osmosis. Osmosis is the movement of water across a semipermeable membrane from an area of lower solute concentration to an area of higher solute concentration.\r\n\r\nAs water enters the RBCs, they begin to swell and may eventually burst or lyse if the influx of water becomes too great. This is because the RBC membrane can only stretch to a certain extent before rupturing.","reference":"Lopez MJ, Hall CA. Physiology, osmosis. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed October 3, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557609/","responses":[{"text":"Swell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shrink","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Burst","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Remain same","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crenate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21589,"text":"A pharmacologist invents a new drug and experiments with it on a human volunteer. What is the earliest evidence that the drug is most likely being  stored in tissue?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 10.","responses":[{"text":"Increased plasma protein bounding","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased rate of drug metabolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased amount of free drug excreted in the urine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A large volume of distribution","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased number of side effects","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

export default a